{"ts":"2026-06-27T08:27:37.482Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Constructing the \"No Session\" UI**\n\nI'm structuring the new `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx` step-by-step. The focus now is the \"No Session Detected / Session Expired\" screen. The premium hero header will include a \"SECURITY DECOUPLING PROTOCOL\" tag, \"DECENTRALIZED WORKSPACE DECOUPLED\" heading, and a description. A visual metaphor of a zero-trust decoupled security model will be a grid of interactive nodes with pulsing connections and telemetry.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T08:27:39.494Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Simulating the Workspace Roles**\n\nI'm now diving into the \"Workspace Simulation Dock\" within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. The goal is a highly engaging sandbox experience. Key features include the \"DECRYPT & FORCE LAUNCH SANDBOX\" action card. Also, I'm thinking about a countdown to auto-redirect the user if they do not want the simulation, or the \"SIMULATE SESSION\" option. This will present a grid of mock roles (Client Admin, GFF Sovereign Admin, etc.) that users can test with. Each card will have descriptions, tiers, hover effects, and a simulation for each role.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T08:27:41.475Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Visualizing the Access Block**\n\nI'm now designing the \"Clearance Insufficient\" screen within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. My focus is a premium hero header featuring \"ENCLAVE BOUNDARY PROTECTION\" as a tag, \"ACCESS BLOCK: LEVEL INSUFFICIENT\" as the main heading, and a strategic explanation of clearance levels. I'm also planning an interactive visual metaphor, an active access control matrix, illustrating the clearance hierarchy, current role with a warning, target section's required role, and a firewall block.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T08:27:43.524Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Implementing Role Bypass**\n\nI'm now integrating an enhanced authorization gateway within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. Instead of a standard error, a sophisticated panel will appear. It will include a secondary button to de-escalate to the dashboard, and a feature to elevate or swap authorized roles. This bypass functionality dynamically lists applicable roles based on the target section, allowing instant and educational role testing via the \"AUTHORIZE & DECRYPT\" action that executes `handleBypass(role)`. I'll also be checking current role definitions in `lib/preview-auth.ts`.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T08:27:44.650Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Defining Access Controls**\n\nI'm now detailing portal and admin section access controls. I have defined roles and the corresponding sections they can access, including `gff_admin`, `viewer`, `client_member`, and several others. This is a critical step for granular role-based authorization within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. This detailed breakdown will inform the dynamic role bypass mechanism.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T08:27:46.391Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Refining Role Authorization**\n\nI am now structuring role and section authorization within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. My focus is on creating a helper function, `getAuthorizedRoles()`, to determine which roles are authorized for specific route segments. I am also implementing a `RoleMeta` lookup object to store role-specific metadata like title, clearance level, description, badge color and border color. These metadata will enhance user feedback and improve the UI.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
