{"ts":"2026-06-27T08:28:20.800Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Addressing the Build Timeout**\n\nThe build command timed out, a common occurrence with full static Next.js builds on larger sites. I'm focusing on crafting a premium, custom UI within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx` for both \"No Session\" and \"Clearance Insufficient\" screens.\n\n\n**Constructing the \"No Session\" UI**\n\nI'm structuring the new `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx` step-by-step. The focus now is the \"No Session Detected / Session Expired\" screen. The premium hero header will include a \"SECURITY DECOUPLING PROTOCOL\" tag, \"DECENTRALIZED WORKSPACE DECOUPLED\" heading, and a description. A visual metaphor of a zero-trust decoupled security model will be a grid of interactive nodes with pulsing connections and telemetry.\n\n\n**Simulating the Workspace Roles**\n\nI'm now diving into the \"Workspace Simulation Dock\" within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. The goal is a highly engaging sandbox experience. Key features include the \"DECRYPT & FORCE LAUNCH SANDBOX\" action card. Also, I'm thinking about a countdown to auto-redirect the user if they do not want the simulation, or the \"SIMULATE SESSION\" option. This will present a grid of mock roles (Client Admin, GFF Sovereign Admin, etc.) that users can test with. Each card will have descriptions, tiers, hover effects, and a simulation for each role.\n\n\n**Visualizing the Access Block**\n\nI'm now designing the \"Clearance Insufficient\" screen within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. My focus is a premium hero header featuring \"ENCLAVE BOUNDARY PROTECTION\" as a tag, \"ACCESS BLOCK: LEVEL INSUFFICIENT\" as the main heading, and a strategic explanation of clearance levels. I'm also planning an interactive visual metaphor, an active access control matrix, illustrating the clearance hierarchy, current role with a warning, target section's required role, and a firewall block.\n\n\n**Implementing Role Bypass**\n\nI'm now integrating an enhanced authorization gateway within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. Instead of a standard error, a sophisticated panel will appear. It will include a secondary button to de-escalate to the dashboard, and a feature to elevate or swap authorized roles. This bypass functionality dynamically lists applicable roles based on the target section, allowing instant and educational role testing via the \"AUTHORIZE & DECRYPT\" action that executes `handleBypass(role)`. I'll also be checking current role definitions in `lib/preview-auth.ts`.\n\n\n**Defining Access Controls**\n\nI'm now detailing portal and admin section access controls. I have defined roles and the corresponding sections they can access, including `gff_admin`, `viewer`, `client_member`, and several others. This is a critical step for granular role-based authorization within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. This detailed breakdown will inform the dynamic role bypass mechanism.\n\n\n**Refining Role Authorization**\n\nI am now structuring role and section authorization within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. My focus is on creating a helper function, `getAuthorizedRoles()`, to determine which roles are authorized for specific route segments. I am also implementing a `RoleMeta` lookup object to store role-specific metadata like title, clearance level, description, badge color and border color. These metadata will enhance user feedback and improve the UI.\n\n\n**Implementing Role Data**\n\nI'm now detailing `RoleMeta` lookups within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. I am defining properties for each role, including title, clearance level, description, badge color and border color. My focus is on enriching UI feedback and refining the user experience. This data will directly inform the visual representation and interactive elements of the role authorization mechanism.\n\n\n**Enhancing Role Visuals**\n\nI'm now integrating detailed `RoleMeta` details within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. Properties for each role, like clearance, description, and color scheme, are added for visual enrichment. My focus is on enriching the user feedback through visual elements such as badge colors and borders. The goal is to provide a more intuitive and informative UI.\n\n\n**Visualizing Access Block Diagram**\n\nI am now designing the interactive \"Enclave Clearance Diagram\" for the \"Clearance Insufficient\" screen within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. My idea is a vertical stack representing clearance levels, from I to V. Each level, color-coded and labeled (Auditor to Superuser), will be a node on the stack. The current role is highlighted, and the target section's required level is displayed, along with a firewall visual.\n\n\n**Designing the Block Diagram**\n\nI'm now integrating an interactive \"Enclave Clearance Diagram\" for the \"Clearance Insufficient\" screen within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. The design will be a CSS/SVG panel displaying clearance tiers. I'll highlight the necessary clearance with a glowing aura and a lock. For instance, if the user is Level II and needs Level III, a dotted line with an animated pulse wave will connect their level to the Firewall Block. This approach provides a clear visual representation of access restrictions.\n\n\n**Visualizing Clearance Tiers**\n\nI'm now detailing the \"Enclave Clearance Diagram.\" I plan to display clearance tiers as horizontal blocks, stacked from Level I to V. Each block will display the level, name, and representative roles. Active and authorized roles will be indicated with badges and checkmarks. Blocked access levels will display a lock. This interactive SVG will enhance the visual clarity of the clearance structure and improve user understanding.\n\n\n**Visualizing Data Connections**\n\nI'm now integrating an interactive visual representation of data connections within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. This includes an animated grid background and stylized connection lines. I'm focusing on making the connections visually appealing, with subtle pulsations and dashed patterns. Node visuals will be next, with interactive elements to enrich the user experience of the security overview.\n\n\n**Visualizing Security Nodes**\n\nI'm now focusing on the interactive node visuals within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. Specifically, I'm integrating data connections with an animated grid background. The connection lines will feature subtle pulsations and dashed patterns for visual appeal. Next, I am thinking of node visualizations, with interactive elements. These enhancements will improve the user experience of the security overview.\n\n\n**Refining Visual Integration**\n\nI'm now integrating the SVG code for the access block visuals within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`, focusing on incorporating the provided SVG and CSS-compatible visuals to improve the presentation of restricted areas. I have identified a clean SVG approach to better visualize restricted areas and clearance discrepancies. This visual integration aims to enhance the user experience by delivering a clear and intuitive representation of access restrictions.\n\n\n**Enhancing Role Bypass**\n\nI'm now refining the role bypass within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. My focus is on redirecting users to their originally requested route after role elevation, not just the dashboard. I can access the `pathname` to determine the target route after the bypass is executed. This should dramatically improve user experience after bypassing access blocks.\n\n\n**Implementing Route Persistence**\n\nI'm now refining the role bypass in `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx` to keep the user on the same route. After role elevation, I'm checking if the new role has access to the originally requested route, and redirecting the user there if it is permitted. This prevents a jarring experience of being redirected to the dashboard after a successful bypass. I'm also implementing checks to gracefully redirect back to the dashboard if a role doesn't permit access to the requested segment.\n\n\n**Verifying Countdown Behavior**\n\nI've tested the countdown behavior for \"No Session\" scenarios. Landing on `/portal/dashboard` with no session now correctly redirects to `/portal/login` after 4 seconds. The countdown is properly interrupted if a role is selected before completion, and the login proceeds smoothly because of `session` updates. The `useEffect` hook ensures this only runs when the `session` state is null, as intended.\n\n\n**Refining Fallback Redirect**\n\nI'm now implementing context-aware login redirects within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. The goal is to provide a user experience that adapts to the current section. Now, the fallback logic will intelligently determine the correct login URL (`/admin/login` or `/portal/login`) based on the detected route, ensuring a seamless user experience.\n\n**Designing the Layout**\n\nI'm now working on the responsive layout in `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx` for the \"No Session\" screen. I'm aiming for a full-screen split layout on desktop using CSS Grid and a stacked layout on mobile. The design will feature a visual diagram on one side and simulation controls on the other, enhancing user engagement and clarity.\n\n\n**Designing the Layout**\n\nI'm now detailing the full-screen, split layouts for both \"Session Expired\" and \"Clearance Insufficient\" screens within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. The \"Session Expired\" layout is a full screen grid, featuring a telemetry log terminal on the left side with a zero-trust architecture diagram and the simulation controls on the right side. The \"Clearance Insufficient\" layout will use a similar grid with an \"Enclave Clearance Matrix Diagram\" on the left and elevation controls on the right.\n\n\n**Refining UI Details**\n\nI am now focusing on refining the UI details for both the \"Clearance Insufficient\" and \"Session Expired\" screens within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. For the \"Clearance Insufficient\" screen, I'm integrating the provided telemetry log terminal into the left panel alongside the \"Clearance Stack\" diagram. For the \"Session Expired\" screen, the right panel will feature the elements: `DECOUPLED GATEWAY` cyber-border tag, \"Enclave Session Expired\" heading, a clarifying description, and the interactive countdown timer.\n\n\n**Designing the Access Paths**\n\nI'm now detailing the \"Clearance Insufficient\" screen within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`. The right panel will include a `CLEARANCE BOUNDARY VIOLATION` cyber-border tag, a \"Clearance Insufficient\" heading, and a description clarifying the issue. It will also show the simulated profile's role and the inaccessible section. A new section, \"PERMITTED ACCESS PATHS\", will guide users on resolving the block, either by returning to their dashboard or temporarily elevating their simulated role. A loading spinner will activate upon click on the role.\n\n\n\n**Validating Role Definitions**\n\nI'm now integrating a dynamic grid within `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx` to display authorized roles based on the requested section, fetched using `getAuthorizedRoles(type, activeSec)`. Each role card includes title, clearance level, description, and an \"ELEVATE & TRAVERSE\" action. A \"Return to Safety Dashboard\" button is also added. I'm verifying the roles defined in `lib/preview-auth.ts`, specifically: `client_admin`, `client_member`, `gff_admin`, `gff_operator`, `finance_admin`, `support_agent`, and `viewer`, to ensure validity and coverage. I am considering edge cases, specifically invalid sections.\n\n\n"}}
