{"ts":"2026-06-27T08:29:06.208Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Confirming Consistency and Design**\n\nI'm incredibly pleased to see every file uniformly utilizes `motion/react`! This is a major win for seamless implementation. Now, I'm focusing on crafting a custom design within `components/private-app/PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`--I'm feeling excited.\n\n\n**Analyzing Component Structure**\n\nI'm now diving into the specifics of `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`, mapping its state variables and functionality. I've noted its authentication and authorization handling, including the admin banner. I am going to refine the banner design to be more polished; I am thinking of a clean capsule design.\n\n\n**Refining Style and Guardrails**\n\nI'm working to design an elegant, minimalist admin bar for the route guard, ensuring it doesn't disrupt the layout. Simultaneously, I'm meticulously reviewing the guardrails document and user requirements to ensure strict adherence, especially regarding landing page modifications, component recreation, and forbidden backend elements. My aim is to create a premium, Apple-like UI, avoiding common pitfalls such as excessive visual clutter.\n\n\n**Prioritizing Mobile Optimization and Premium Design**\n\nI'm now prioritizing mobile responsiveness and accessibility in the design. I will run lint/build checks following substantive updates. I'm aiming for a sophisticated, spacious aesthetic, steering clear of common UI pitfalls and embracing a \"Modern\", \"Calm\", \"Strategic\" feel. I am focused on a high-end visual language with neutral dark grays, fine hairline borders, and subtle glows, leveraging high-end typography choices to give the design an expensive and calming look. I've begun planning the file structure for `/components/private-app/PreviewRouteGuard.tsx` as well.\n\n\n**Defining Role Metadata**\n\nI've just defined the `ROLE_METADATA` object, mapping preview roles to metadata. Each role includes a title, clearance level, description, badge class, and glow color, all ready for use in the UI. I've considered how these elements contribute to the overall user experience and clarity within the route guard.\n\n\n**Expanding Role Metadata**\n\nI've been expanding the `ROLE_METADATA` to include several new roles: a GFF Systems Engineer, a Financial Director, and a Support Liaison. Each role has a distinct badge color, clearance level, and descriptive title. I want to convey an immediate sense of role and responsibility. I'm focusing on consistency in the metadata's data structure and design to maintain a polished UI feel.\n\n\n**Designing Terminal Logs**\n\nI'm now focusing on a terminal simulator component for the \"No Session Detected\" message, planning a visual box for the left column. I'm exploring an initial set of logs for the simulation, emphasizing a secure tunnel protocol and boundary verification. It's designed to give a sense of active security measures and engagement, enhancing the user's perception of the application.\n\n\n**Simulating Terminal Output**\n\nI'm now generating realistic terminal logs for the \"No Session Detected\" message, aiming to instill a sense of urgency and security. To keep things varied, I've incorporated random phrases focusing on cryptographic keys, verification sessions, and security protocols to make the UI engaging. The objective is to visually reinforce the application's robust security posture.\n\n\n**Visualizing Clearance Insufficiency**\n\nI'm working on the \"Clearance Insufficient\" display, designing a vertical timeline/tree to show security clearance tiers. I'm using `CLEARANCE_TIERS` to define levels like \"Federated Control,\" \"Systems Engineer,\" and \"Workspace Admin,\" each with specific roles, names, and badges. It's designed to give a clear visual path for access and is intended to be easily understandable.\n\n\n**Visualizing Clearance Tiers**\n\nI'm now implementing the vertical timeline for `CLEARANCE_TIERS`, ensuring each level visually represents access. I'm focusing on highlighting the current user's tier and if the route is allowed, along with role checks. My goal is to create an intuitive visualization of security clearance levels, and the access rights associated with it.\n\n\n\n**Implementing Access Controls**\n\nI am now implementing access control using the `canAccessPortalSection` and `canAccessAdminSection` functions. These are used within a role check, evaluating permissions based on the active security context and type. I'm dynamically updating the UI to reflect user access, focusing on real-time permission enforcement within the vertical clearance tier visualization.\n\n\n**Enhancing UI Visuals**\n\nI'm now focusing on enhancing the visual feedback of clearance tiers. I'm dynamically updating the UI with custom CSS, like different backgrounds, and subtle glows. I am leveraging conditional styling to differentiate between current, allowed, and disallowed access points. This will reinforce security through intuitive visual cues.\n\n\n**Refining Tier Display**\n\nI'm now refining the visual clarity of the clearance tiers, ensuring a clear display of active, allowed, and restricted states using distinct labels. I've focused on subtle visual cues and informative text to enhance the overall understanding of each tier within the timeline.\n\n\n**Confirming Component Implementation**\n\nI'm now writing the complete code for `PreviewRouteGuard.tsx`, focusing on implementing the custom hero visual, SVG graphic, and narrative timeline. I've confirmed that `motion/react` can be imported cleanly and I'm integrating it for smoother animations. I am also working to ensure a strong visual hierarchy and calm, premium aesthetic.\n\n\n**Defining Role Simulation**\n\nI'm now defining the structure for the simulation profiles, to be rendered as role selection cards. I'm focusing on \"Enclave Session Expired\" scenarios and will render the core profiles. This includes GFF Sovereign Super-Admin, Client Administrator, Systems Engineer, and Client Workspace Operator roles. My goal is a streamlined, intuitive interface.\n\n\n**Implementing Role Cards**\n\nI'm now building role selection cards within the \"No Session\" layout using the provided `SIM_PROFILES`. These display role metadata dynamically, creating interactive options for bypass scenarios. I'm focusing on visually distinct card designs, including subtle glows for the active profile, to achieve an intuitive selection experience.\n\n\n**Finalizing Simulation & Bypassing**\n\nI've just finalized role simulation, ensuring instant session bypass via role card selection. I'm leveraging distinct visuals like custom clearances, badge styling, and subtle glows for an intuitive selection experience. Each card now includes metadata for its respective clearance level, facilitating smoother transitions.\n\n\n**Visualizing Role Swaps**\n\nI'm now rendering authorized roles in a grid for \"Clearance Insufficient\" scenarios. I've designed interactive role swap options, leveraging `ROLE_METADATA` for display. I'm excited; I'm implementing dynamic visuals, subtle glows, and disabled states during negotiation. This should elevate the user experience.\n\n\n**Refining Swap Visualization**\n\nI'm now refining the role swap visuals. I'm focusing on disabled states and glow effects to provide feedback during negotiation. The visuals are designed to communicate clearly to the user, enhancing interaction and understanding.\n\n\n**Refining Loading Bar**\n\nI'm now refining the countdown progress bar for a seamless user experience, and I'm very excited about the progress. I've integrated a loading bar that's synchronized with the countdown timer. I am using dynamic styles to accurately reflect time elapsed, and ensuring the UI provides clear feedback during the dissociation process. I am double-checking how the terminal secure socket integrates.\n\n\n**Confirming Banner Implementation**\n\nI'm now implementing the top bar admin banner for GFF admins within client spaces. I've integrated a sleek visual layout, confirming it only appears when `isAdminInPortal` is active. I've incorporated a dynamic `duration-1000 ease-linear` effect for a smooth appearance, enhancing the visual flow. I'm focusing on ensuring it cleanly integrates with existing UI elements.\n\n\n**Enhancing Banner Appearance**\n\nI'm now refining the admin banner's visual aesthetic. I've switched to a floating capsule design with fine border styling for a polished look. I am incorporating subtle animation effects to make it feel more premium and engaging, ensuring it subtly hovers above the content.\n\n\n**Refining Security Visuals**\n\nI'm now implementing the admin session active banner and am working on visual feedback for secure sessions. The session indicators will use real-time visual cues to communicate secure states and clearance levels effectively, creating a premium interface.\n\n\n**Reviewing Sidebar and Topbar**\n\nI'm now investigating `sidebar-topbar.tsx` to ensure role access is correctly reflected and styled consistently with the rest of the application. I'm focusing on incorporating a streamlined design that aligns with the premium aesthetic of the admin banner and other elements.\n\n\n"}}
